  "prompt": "What is the average salary of an MBA graduate in India?",
  "response": "The average salary of an MBA graduate in India can vary significantly based on factors such as the business school, specialization, work experience, industry, and location. As of recent data (2022-2023), here are some general insights:\n\n1. **Top-tier B-Schools (e.g., IIMs, ISB, XLRI):**  \n   - Graduates from premier institutions like the Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs) or the Indian School of Business (ISB) often command higher salaries.  \n   - The average starting salary ranges from **\u20b920 lakhs to \u20b935 lakhs per annum** (approximately $25,000 to $43,000 USD).  \n   - For top performers, salaries can exceed **\u20b950 lakhs per annum** or more.\n\n2. **Mid-tier B-Schools:**  \n   - Graduates from reputable but not elite institutions typically earn between **\u20b910 lakhs to \u20b920 lakhs per annum** (approximately $12,000 to $25,000 USD).\n\n3. **General MBA Programs:**  \n   - Graduates from smaller or lesser-known institutions may earn between **\u20b95 lakhs to \u20b912 lakhs per annum** (approximately $6,000 to $15,000 USD).\n\n### Factors Influencing Salaries:\n- **Specialization:** Fields like finance, consulting, and technology tend to offer higher salaries compared to other sectors.  \n- **Location:** Metropolitan cities like Mumbai, Delhi, and Bangalore often offer higher salaries due to the concentration of corporate offices and industries.  \n- **Work Experience:** Candidates with prior work experience generally command higher salaries compared to freshers.  \n\n### Industry-Specific Trends:\n- **Consulting:** Average salary ranges from **\u20b918 lakhs to \u20b935 lakhs per annum**.  \n- **Finance:** Average salary ranges from **\u20b915 lakhs to \u20b930 lakhs per annum**.  \n- **Technology/IT:** Average salary ranges from **\u20b912 lakhs to \u20b925 lakhs per annum**.  \n\nThese figures are approximate and can vary depending on market conditions and individual profiles. For the most accurate data, it\u2019s best to refer to the latest placement reports of specific business schools.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
